aa(lp70
VAge is another thing
p71
aVwhen our attitude toward our appearance changes.
p72
aVSo children judge themselves, learn to judge themselves,
p73
aVby the behavior of adults around them.
p74
aVHere's a classic example: Rebecca has a benign blood vessel tumor
p75
aVthat's growing out through her skull, has obliterated her nose,
p76
aVand she's having difficulty seeing.
p77
aVAs you can see, it's blocking her vision.
p78
aVShe's also in danger, when she damages this,
p79
aVof bleeding profusely.
p80
aVOur research has shown
p81
aVthat the parents and close loved ones of these children
p82
aVadore them.
p83
aVThey've grown used to their face; they think they're special.
p84
aVActually, sometimes the parents argue
p85
aVabout whether these children should have the lesion removed.
p86
aVAnd occasionally they suffer intense grief reactions
p87
aVbecause the child they've grown to love
p88
aVhas changed so dramatically and they don't recognize them.
p89
aVBut other adults
p90
aVsay incredibly painful things.
p91
aVThey say, "How dare you take this child out of the house
p92
aVand terrify other people.
p93
aVShouldn't you be doing something about this? Why haven't you had it removed?"
p94
aVAnd other children in curiosity come up and poke the lesion,
p95
aVbecause \u2014 a natural curiosity.
p96
aVAnd that obviously alerts the child
p97
aVto their unusual nature.
p98
aVAfter surgery, everything normalizes.
p99
aVThe adults behave more naturally,
p100
aVand the children play more readily with other children.
