aa(lp161
VWhen people get older,
p162
aVthey don't necessarily choose to follow this kind of surgery.
p163
aVTheir presence in the consultation suite
p164
aVis a result of the slings and arrows of outrageous fortune.
p165
aVWhat happens to them
p166
aVis that they may have suffered cancer or trauma.
p167
aVSo this is a photograph of Henry,
p168
aVtwo weeks after he had a malignant cancer removed
p169
aVfrom the left side of his face \u2014 his cheekbone,
p170
aVhis upper jaw, his eye-socket.
p171
aVHe looks pretty good at this stage.
p172
aVBut over the course of the next 15 years he had 14 more operations,
p173
aVas the disease ravaged his face
p174
aVand destroyed my reconstruction regularly.
p175
aVI learned a huge amount from Henry.
p176
aVHenry taught me
p177
aVthat you can carry on working.
p178
aVHe worked as an advocate. He continued to play cricket.
p179
aVHe enjoyed life to the full,
p180
aVand this was probably because he had a successful, fulfilling job
p181
aVand a caring family
p182
aVand was able to participate socially.
p183
aVHe maintained a calm insouciance.
p184
aVI don't say he overcame this; he didn't overcome it.
p185
aVThis was something more than that. He ignored it.
p186
aVHe ignored the disfigurement that was happening in his life
p187
aVand carried on oblivious to it.
p188
aVAnd that's what these people can do.
