aa(lp210
VSo we've seen that we can change people's faces.
p211
aVBut when we change people's faces,
p212
aVare we changing their identity \u2014
p213
aVfor better or for worse?
p214
aVFor instance,
p215
aVthere are two different types of facial surgery.
p216
aVWe can categorize it like that.
p217
aVWe can say there are patients who choose to have facial surgery \u2014
p218
aVlike Sue.
p219
aVWhen they have facial surgery,
p220
aVthey feel their lives have changed
p221
aVbecause other people perceive them
p222
aVas better people.
p223
aVThey don't feel different.
p224
aVThey feel that they've actually gained
p225
aVwhat they never had,
p226
aVthat their face now reflects their personality.
p227
aVAnd actually that's probably the difference between cosmetic surgery
p228
aVand this kind of surgery.
p229
aVBecause you might say, "Well, this type of surgery
p230
aVmight be regarded as cosmetic."
p231
aVIf you do cosmetic surgery, patients are often less happy.
p232
aVThey're trying to achieve difference in their lives.
p233
aVSue wasn't trying to achieve difference in her life.
p234
aVShe was just trying to achieve the face
p235
aVthat matched her personality.
p236
aa(lp237
VBut then we have other people
p238
aVwho don't choose to have facial surgery.
p239
aVThey're people who have their face shot off.
p240
aVI'll move it off, and we'll have a blank slide for those who are squeamish amongst you.
p241
aVThey have it forced upon them.
p242
aVAnd again, as I told you,
p243
aVif they have a caring family
p244
aVand good work life,
p245
aVthen they can lead normal and fulfilled lives.
p246
aVTheir identity doesn't change.
