aa(lp264
VWe make judgments on people's faces
p265
aVall the time.
p266
aVIt's been going on since we can think of Lombroso
p267
aVand the way he would define criminal faces.
p268
aVHe said you could see criminal faces,
p269
aVjudging them just on the photographs that were showed.
p270
aVGood-looking people
p271
aVare always judged as being more friendly.
p272
aVWe look at O.J. \u2014
p273
aVhe's a good-looking guy.
p274
aVWe'd like to spend time with him. He looks friendly.
p275
aVNow we know that he's a convicted wife-batterer,
p276
aVand actually he's not the good guy.
p277
aVAnd beauty doesn't equate to goodness,
p278
aVand certainly doesn't equate to contentment.
p279
aa(lp280
VSo we've talked about the static face
p281
aVand judging the static face,
p282
aVbut actually, we're more comfortable
p283
aVwith judging the moving face.
p284
aVWe think we can judge people on their expressions.
p285
aVU.K. jurors in the U.K. justice system
p286
aVlike to see a live witness
p287
aVto see whether they can pick up the telltale signs of mendacity \u2014
p288
aVthe blink, the hesitation.
p289
aVAnd so they want to see live witnesses.
p290
aVTodorov tells us that, in a tenth of a second,
p291
aVwe can make a judgment on somebody's face.
p292
aVAre we uncomfortable with this image? Yes, we are.
p293
aVWould we be happy if our doctor's face, our lawyer's face,
p294
aVour financial adviser's face was covered?
p295
aVWe'd be pretty uncomfortable.
p296
aVBut are we good at making the judgments
p297
aVon facial appearance and movement?
p298
aVThe truth is that there's a five-minute rule,
p299
aVnot the tenth-of-a-second rule like Todorov, but a five-minute rule.
p300
aVIf you spend five minutes with somebody,
p301
aVyou start looking beyond their facial appearance,
p302
aVand the people who you're initially attracted to
p303
aVmay seem boring and you lose interest in them,
p304
aVand the people who you didn't immediately seek out,
p305
aVbecause you didn't find them particularly attractive,
p306
aVbecome attractive people
p307
aVbecause of their personality.
